text: Sure. That's probably a risk. I haven't found that to be true in practice. I think that if we're being practical and you go out there and you look at some of these alternative options to indexing and market cap weighing, call it like equal weighing or some of these momentum ETFs that have come out, some of these different factor implementations that have come out alongside. And we've discussed it previously. I mean, some of these implementations are extremely naive in how they do it. And I think the complexity of implementation when you are doing a systematic product is a double-edged sword. You can try to improve on, call it your academic factors, but you're going to be benchmarked to those academic factors. So you better make sure that your implementation is going to outperform at the correct times, or at least not underperform when you're up for review, because that could turn very ugly for you very quickly. And if that's the benchmark, there's really, I mean, obviously everybody wants to do better, but there's also this incentive of like, well, that's what they're paying you for. That's what they asked you to do. That's what you should deliver. You could try to upsell them on something better, but ultimately these institutions are sophisticated. They know what they want. You're not talking to like Joe Retail that needs handholding. If that's what they're asking you to implement, that's what you deliver. And so that's one of the reasons I think that a naive implementation works best. And the other one is that you're going to get a lot of money, you're going to get a mix of a lot of different implementations. And if you start getting into the details of some of them, you're going to miss how the collective behave, right? You need to have that common root implementation, right? And you're going to miss details. You're going to have information loss at the edges, but ultimately it's going to catch the right signals when you really need them. You're going to lose a lot of smaller signals, but the big ones you're not going to miss.
